Attempt Different Combination of variables

From the Kaplan-Meier Curve, we know that variable with smallest p-value is ‘TOTAE’(Total Adverse Event). In this section, we are trying to use different combinations of variables and use them in AFT model to see if we can get any significant variables in these combinations and which combination makes the model better. We will start with only TOTAE(Total Adverse Event) First.

Code 
#AFT Model
m1<- survreg(Surv(AVAL,1-CNSR) ~  TOTAE  , 
    data = d_s )
tidy(m1)
# A tibble: 3 × 5
  term        estimate std.error statistic  p.value
  <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl>
1 (Intercept)   6.63      0.0551    120.   0       
2 TOTAE        -0.0248    0.0190     -1.31 1.91e- 1
3 Log(scale)   -0.625     0.0417    -15.0  8.93e-51

From the result above, the TOTAE column is not significant(p-value greater than 0.05) when using it in a AFT model by itself. Now we want to find the combinations of variables that makes a model a good fit for the data.

Code 
candidate_vars <- c("TRT01P", "TOTAE", "SAECOUNT","AEDECOD_MS","AEBODSYS","AESER","AGE","SEX","RACE","ETHNIC","LDH","ALB","HGB","BMI","ECOG","CRP")

model_list <- list()

# Generate all combinations of the candidate variables (from 1 to n variables)
combos <- lapply(1:length(candidate_vars), function(n) combn(candidate_vars, n, simplify = FALSE))

# Flatten the list of combinations
combos <- unlist(combos, recursive = FALSE)

# Initialize the base model (just the intercept)
base_model <- survreg(Surv(AVAL, 1-CNSR) ~ 1, data = d_s, dist = "weibull")

# Fit models for each combination of variables
for (i in 1:length(combos)) {
  # Create the formula for the combination of variables
  combo_formula <- paste("Surv(AVAL, 1-CNSR) ~", paste(combos[[i]], collapse = " + "))
  
  # Fit the model
  new_model <- survreg(as.formula(combo_formula), data = d_s, dist = "weibull")
  
  # Store the model in model_list
  model_list[[i]] <- new_model
  
}

length(combos)
[1] 65535

As you can see, there are 65535 combinations of variables. Now we want to get the top ten models that has the lowest AIC scores. AIC score is a criteria that measures how well a statistical model fits the data. Lower AIC indicates better fit.

Code 
# Initialize a data frame to store model AICs
aic_scores <- data.frame(
  model_id = integer(),
  variables = character(),
  aic = numeric()
)

# Calculate the AIC for each model and store the results
for (i in seq_along(model_list)) {
  # Extract the model
  model <- model_list[[i]]
  
  # Get the AIC and variable combination
  aic <- AIC(model)
  vars <- paste(attr(model$terms, "term.labels"), collapse = ", ")
  
  # Append to the data frame
  aic_scores <- rbind(aic_scores, data.frame(
    model_id = i,
    variables = vars,
    aic = aic
  ))
}

# Sort by AIC in ascending order and get the top 10
top_10_models <- aic_scores[order(aic_scores$aic), ][1:10, ]

# Print the top 10 models with their AICs
print(top_10_models)

From the result above, we can see that the model with only TOTAE(Total Adverse Event) as a variable has the lowest AIC score. However, the difference of the AIC scores among the top ten models are not huge. And we don’t see any significant variables among these models.

Now we want to use the Cox-Snell residual plots to compare how good each models fit the data.

Code 
# Loop through the top 10 models and generate Cox-Snell Residual plots
for (i in 1:nrow(top_10_models)) {
  model_id <- top_10_models$model_id[i]
  model <- model_list[[model_id]]
  
  # Calculate Cox-Snell residuals
  cox_snell_resid <- d_s$AVAL * exp(-predict(model, type = "lp"))
  
  # Fit a Kaplan-Meier survival curve to the Cox-Snell residuals
  km_fit <- survfit(Surv(cox_snell_resid, 1 - CNSR) ~ 1, data = d_s)
  
  # Calculate cumulative hazard
  cum_hazard <- -log(km_fit$surv)
  
  # Plot Cox-Snell residuals
  plot(
    km_fit$time, cum_hazard,
    type = "l",
    xlab = "Cox-Snell Residuals",
    ylab = "Cumulative Hazard",
    main = paste("Cox-Snell Residuals for Model", i, "with Variables:", top_10_models$variables[i]),
    col = "blue",
    lwd = 2
  )
  abline(a = 0, b = 1, col = "red", lty = 2)
}

Even though the model with only TOTAE(Total Adverse Event) as a variable has the lowest AIC score, we don’t see any significant variables among these models. We now want to see the AIC scores of the model with the variables that we selected and check if there are any significant variables in it.

We compare the two models and find out that both of the two model doesn’t contain any significant variables. Now we want to compare their cox-snell residual plot and see if there is a big difference.

Code

Although 7 point is a substantial difference for AIC score, we don’t see much difference from the plots above and the p value of TOTAE(Total Adverse Event) only differentiate by 0.01. Based on the reason that we select the features, we believe we can keep our selected model and make interpretation on it.

For AFT models, if the coefficient is negative, that means increase in risk which cause the log survive time to decrease. In our result, Among all the variables, only LDH(Lactate Dehydrogenase) has a positive value, which indicates that every unit increase in LDH(Lactate Dehydrogenase), the log of survival time increase by 0.002. The TRT10P（Treatment group) has a negative value which indicates that Treatment B decrease the log survival time by 0.04 compare to Treatment A. Being a male also decrease the log survival time by 0.01 compare to being a female. All the other variables indicates ab decrease in log survival time.
